					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">MottZilla wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">the lines you'd see in a CRT aren't going to match up with every NES line of pixels.</div>Where did you hear that piece of misinformation? <img src="./images/smilies/icon_neutral.gif" alt=":|" title="Neutral" /> <br /><br />The lines on (most) CRT TVs correspond exactly to the lines of the input video signal. A typical 480i signal is interlaced, so the lines alternate between two patterns. Some TVs will narrow the beam enough that there is blank space between scanlines, since a typical interlaced signal will fill in those blank spaces 1/60th of a second later. Since the NES produces a progressive video signal, those spaces never get filled in, which makes them much more apparent than they'd normally be.</div>

